     Some people who  shares a computer has private,  dangerous or own-made
     programs.  It  is  difficult  to ensure  that  nobody  will  run  that
     conflictive program while  you are not present. Lets  imagine an adult
     who shares his computer with a little brother. How can he be sure that
     some programs are  not run ? Just imagine  the risk of  executing some
     programs  such as  PCTOOLS,  DISKEDIT  or simply  DELTREE by  a person
     without much knowledge.  Of course you can hide these  files using the
     ATTRIB command, or rename them into non-executable extensions (such as
     .PRG) or even  encript them using some encripting  software, but these
     are  little tricks,  not  true solutions.  They  are time-wasting  and
     unprofessional. It would be better if the called program asks the user
     for a password or a key. This is how FPS works.

  ÚÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ¿
  ³  IDEA                                                                 ³
  ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÙ

     FPS adds  a little header to  the program so after  being protected it
     asks for a password (password length could be 15 characters long). You
     can specify different passwords for different files. In your passwords
     you  can  include  extrange  characters,  such  as  blanks  and  other
     not-printable  ones. Once  the protected  program is  called, it  will
     display a little  message (that can be changed in  the DELUXE EDITION)
     and prompt  the user for the  string. If it matches  with the password
     which the file was protected with, the file will be run, in other case
     it will return to DOS. NOTE: Passwords ARE CASE SENSITIVE, so "MyProg"
     is different from "MYPROG".


